 <p style="heading">Proemium</p>
 <p style="incipit"><l><locus type="foliation">fol. 1r</locus><space rend="indent1"/><foreign xml:lang="lat">Salve, festa dies I Martis, Mavortis! Avete Kalende! </foreign></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Qua Deus ad celum sublevat ire David!<note type="gloss-indicator" n="1">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="1">(See next three lines)</gloss></l></p><lg><l><space rend="indent1"/>Hail<note type="enote-indicator" n="1">N</note>  <date>Haly Day</date><note type="gloss-indicator" n="2">G</note> devout! Al hail kalende<note type="gloss-indicator" n="3">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="2">Holy Day</gloss><gloss n="3"> kalends (i.e., first day)</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Of <date>Marche</date>,<note type="enote-indicator" n="2">N</note>  wheryn <persName>David</persName> the Confessour</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Commaunded is his Kyngis court ascende!<note target="#1" type="footnotelink">1</note><note type="enote-indicator" n="3">N</note> </l><l><space rend="indent1"/><persName>Emanuel</persName>, <persName>Jhesus the Conquerour</persName>,</l><l><milestone n="5" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>This same day as a tryumphatour,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="4">G</note><space rend="indent2"/><gloss n="4">supreme victor</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Sette in a chare<note type="tnote-indicator" n="1">T</note> <note type="gloss-indicator" n="5">G</note> and throne of majestee,<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="5">chair</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>To <placeName>London</placeName> is comyn.<note type="tnote-indicator" n="2">T</note>  O <persName>Saviour</persName>,</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Welcome a thousand fold to Thi citee!</l></lg>
 <lg><l><space rend="indent1"/>And she, Thi <persName>Modir</persName><note type="gloss-indicator" n="6">G</note> (blessed mot<note type="gloss-indicator" n="7">G</note> she be!)<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="6">Mother (i.e., Mary)</gloss><gloss n="7"> blessed may</gloss></l><l><milestone n="10" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>That cometh eke, and angelys anende,<note type="tnote-indicator" n="3">T</note> <note type="gloss-indicator" n="8">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="8">also, and angels constantly</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Wel-wynged and wel-horsed, hidir fle,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="9">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="9">flying here</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Thousendys on<note type="tnote-indicator" n="4">T</note>  this goode approche attende,</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>And ordir aftir ordir<note type="gloss-indicator" n="10">G</note> thei commende,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="11">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="10">order</gloss><gloss n="11"> they salute</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>As seraphin<note type="gloss-indicator" n="12">G</note>, as cherubyn<note type="gloss-indicator" n="13">G</note>, as throne,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="14">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="12">seraphim</gloss><gloss n="13"> cherubim</gloss><gloss n="14"> thrones</gloss></l><l><milestone n="15" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>As domynaunce<note type="gloss-indicator" n="15">G</note>, and princys<note type="gloss-indicator" n="16">G</note> hidir sende.<note type="enote-indicator" n="4">N</note> <note type="enote-indicator" n="5">N</note> <space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="15">dominions</gloss><gloss n="16"> principalities</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>And, at o<note type="gloss-indicator" n="17">G</note> woord, right welcom everychone!<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="17">one</gloss></l></lg>
 <lg><l><locus type="foliation">fol. 1v</locus><space rend="indent1"/>But Kyng <persName>Herry the Sexte</persName>, as<note type="gloss-indicator" n="18">G</note> <persName>Goddes Sone</persName><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="18">Henry VI, like</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Or th’emperour or Kyng <persName>Emanuel</persName>,</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>To <placeName>London</placeName>, welcomer be noo persone!<note type="gloss-indicator" n="19">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="19">more welcome is no one [but you]</gloss></l><l><milestone n="20" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>O souverayn Lord, welcom! Now wel, now wel!<note type="enote-indicator" n="6">N</note> </l><l><space rend="indent1"/><foreign xml:lang="lat">Te Deum</foreign><note type="enote-indicator" n="7">N</note> <note type="gloss-indicator" n="20">G</note> to be songen, wil do wel,<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="20">‘Thee, O God [we praise]’</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>And <foreign xml:lang="lat">Benedicta Sancta Trinitas</foreign>!<note type="gloss-indicator" n="21">G</note><space rend="indent2"/><gloss n="21">‘Blessed [be] the Holy Trinity’</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Now prosperaunce and peax perpetuel<note type="gloss-indicator" n="22">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="22">prosperity and perpetual peace</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Shal growe. And why? For here is <foreign xml:lang="lat">Unitas</foreign>.<note type="enote-indicator" n="8">N</note> <note type="gloss-indicator" n="23">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="23">‘Unity’</gloss></l></lg>
 <lg><l><milestone n="25" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>Therof to the Unitee: <foreign xml:lang="lat">Deo gratias</foreign><note type="enote-indicator" n="9">N</note> <note type="tnote-indicator" n="5">T</note> <note type="gloss-indicator" n="24">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="24">‘Thanks be to God’</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>In <persName>Trinitee</persName>! The clergys<note type="gloss-indicator" n="25">G</note> and knyghthode<note type="gloss-indicator" n="26">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="25">clergy</gloss><gloss n="26"> knights</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>And comynaltee better accorded nas<note type="gloss-indicator" n="27">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="27">commons better accorded were</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Never then now.<note type="enote-indicator" n="10">N</note>  Now nys ther noon abode,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="28">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="28">Now there is no one facing off</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>But out on hem that fordoon <persName>Goddes</persName> forbode,<note target="#2" type="footnotelink">2</note></l><l><milestone n="30" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>Perjurous ar, rebellous, and atteynte,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="29">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="29">criminal</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>So forfaytinge her lyif and lyvelode,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="30">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="30">forfeiting their lives and livelihood</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Although ypocrisie her faytys peynte.<note type="gloss-indicator" n="31">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="31">hypocrisy disguises their fates</gloss></l></lg>
 <lg><l><space rend="indent1"/>Now, person of <placeName>Caleys</placeName>, pray<note type="gloss-indicator" n="32">G</note> every seynte<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="32">parson of Calais, pray [to]</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>In hevenys and in erth of help: th’availe<note type="gloss-indicator" n="33">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="33">on earth for help: the benefit</gloss></l><l><milestone n="35" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>It is. That in this werk nothing ne feynte,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="34">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="34">nothing be held back</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>But that beforn<note type="gloss-indicator" n="35">G</note> good wynde it go ful sayle;<note type="gloss-indicator" n="36">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="35">before</gloss><gloss n="36"> sail</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>And that not oonly prayer, but travaile<note type="gloss-indicator" n="37">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="37">labor</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Heron be sette. Enserche and faste inquere<note target="#3" type="footnotelink">3</note></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Thi<note type="gloss-indicator" n="38">G</note> litil book <title>Of Knyghthode and Bataile</title><note type="gloss-indicator" n="39">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="38">Your</gloss><gloss n="39"> Battle</gloss></l><l><milestone n="40" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>What chivaler<note type="gloss-indicator" n="40">G</note> is best, on it bewere.<note type="gloss-indicator" n="41">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="40">knight</gloss><gloss n="41"> be advised</gloss></l></lg>
 <p style="heading">[Conversation between the Poet and Beaumont]</p><lg><l><locus type="foliation">fol. 2r</locus><space rend="indent1"/>Whil <foreign xml:lang="lat">Te Deum laudamus</foreign><note type="enote-indicator" n="11">N</note>  up goth<note type="gloss-indicator" n="42">G</note> there<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="42">‘Thee, O God we praise’ is sung</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>At <placeName>Paulis</placeName>,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="43">G</note> up to <placeName>Westmynster</placeName> go thee;<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="43">Paul’s (i.e., St. Paul’s Cathedral)</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>The kyng comyng, <foreign xml:lang="lat">honor</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="lat">virtus</foreign><note type="enote-indicator" n="12">N</note>  the quene,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="44">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="44">[with] ‘virtue’ the queen</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>So glad goth up<note type="gloss-indicator" n="45">G</note> that blisse it is to see.<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="45">Such happiness arises</gloss></l><l><milestone n="45" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>Thi bille<note type="gloss-indicator" n="46">G</note> unto the kyng is red,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="47">G</note> and he<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="46">Your petition</gloss><gloss n="47"> read</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Content withal, and wil it not foryete.<note type="enote-indicator" n="13">N</note> </l><l><space rend="indent1"/>What seith my lord <persName>Beaumont</persName>?<note type="enote-indicator" n="14">N</note>  “Preste,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="48">G</note> unto me<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="48">Priest</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Welcom.” Here is t’assay, entre to gete!<note type="gloss-indicator" n="49">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="49">Now is the test, [with] entry to gain</gloss></l></lg>
 <lg><l><space rend="indent1"/>“Of knyghthode and bataile, my lord, as trete<note type="gloss-indicator" n="50">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="50">as is treated in</gloss></l><l><milestone n="50" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>The bookys olde, a werk is made now late,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="51">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="51">a poem was made of late</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>And if it please you, it may be gete.”<note type="gloss-indicator" n="52">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="52">fetched</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>“What werk is it?” “<persName>Vegetius</persName> translate<note type="gloss-indicator" n="53">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="53">translated</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Into balade.”<note type="gloss-indicator" n="54">G</note> “O preste,<note type="tnote-indicator" n="6">T</note>  I pray thee, late<note type="gloss-indicator" n="55">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="54">Into poetry</gloss><gloss n="55"> let</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Me se that werk.” “Therto wil I you wise.<note type="gloss-indicator" n="56">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="56">I will reveal it to you</gloss></l><l><milestone n="55" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>Lo, here it is!” Anoon<note type="tnote-indicator" n="7">T</note>  he gan therate<note type="gloss-indicator" n="57">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="57">At once he began of it</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>To rede,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="58">G</note> thus: “Sumtyme it was the gise. . .”<note type="enote-indicator" n="15">N</note> <note type="tnote-indicator" n="8">T</note> <note type="gloss-indicator" n="59">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="58">read</gloss><gloss n="59"> fashion</gloss></l></lg>
 <lg><l><space rend="indent1"/>And red<note type="gloss-indicator" n="60">G</note> therof a part. “For my servyse<note type="tnote-indicator" n="9">T</note> <space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="60">read</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Heer wil I rede,” he seith, “as o psaultier.”<note type="gloss-indicator" n="61">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="61">one psalter</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>“It pleaseth you<note type="gloss-indicator" n="62">G</note> right wel. Wil your advyse<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="62">As it pleases you</gloss></l><l><milestone n="60" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>Suppose that<note type="gloss-indicator" n="63">G</note> the kyng heryn pleasier<note type="gloss-indicator" n="64">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="63">Whether</gloss><gloss n="64"> pleasure of this</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>May have?” “I wil considir the matier.</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>I fynde it is right good and pertynente</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Unto the kyng. His celsitude is hier;<note type="gloss-indicator" n="65">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="65">highness is here</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>I halde it wel doon,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="66">G</note> hym therwith presente.”<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="66">consider it well done</gloss></l></lg>
 <p style="heading">[Presentation of the Poem to the King]</p><lg><l><locus type="foliation">fol. 2v</locus><space rend="indent1"/>“<persName>Almyghti Maker</persName> of the firmament,</l><l><milestone n="66" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>O mervailous in every creature,</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>So singuler in<note type="gloss-indicator" n="67">G</note> this most excellent<space rend="indent2"/><gloss n="67">So uniquely present within</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Persone, our souverayn lord!<note type="gloss-indicator" n="68">G</note> Of what stature<space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="68">(i.e., Henry VI)</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Is he, what visagynge,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="69">G</note> how fair-feture,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="70">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="69">visage</gloss><gloss n="70"> fair-featured</gloss></l><l><milestone n="70" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>How myghti mad,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="71">G</note> and how strong in travaile!<note type="gloss-indicator" n="72">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="71">mightily made</gloss><gloss n="72"> works</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>In oonly <persName>God</persName> and hym it is t’assure<note type="gloss-indicator" n="73">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="73">to affirm</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>As in a might, that noo wight dar assaile.<note type="gloss-indicator" n="74">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="74">mighty one, that no person dare assail</gloss></l></lg>
 <lg><l><space rend="indent1"/>“Lo, souverayn lord, <title>Of Knyghthode and Bataile</title>,</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>This litil werk, your humble oratour,</l><l><milestone n="75" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>Ye, therwithal your chivalers, t’availe,</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Inwith your hert to <persName>Crist the Conquerour</persName>,</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Offreth. For ye theryn doeth<note type="tnote-indicator" n="10">T</note>  him th’onour.<note target="#4" type="footnotelink">4</note></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>His true thought, accepte it, he besecheth.<note type="gloss-indicator" n="75">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="75">he (i.e., the poet) begs</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Accepte it is to this tryumphatour</l><l><milestone n="80" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>That myghti werre exemplifying techeth.”<note type="enote-indicator" n="16">N</note> <note type="enote-indicator" n="17">N</note> <note type="gloss-indicator" n="76">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="76">war teaches by examples</gloss></l></lg>
 <lg><l><space rend="indent1"/>He redeth,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="77">G</note> and fro poynt to poynt he secheth,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="78">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="77">reads [it]</gloss><gloss n="78"> searches [it]</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>How hath be doon, and what is now to done;<note target="#5" type="footnotelink">5</note></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>His providence on aftirward he strecheth,</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>By see and lond.<note type="gloss-indicator" n="79">G</note> He wil provide sone<note type="gloss-indicator" n="80">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="79">sea and land</gloss><gloss n="80"> [forces] soon</gloss></l><l><milestone n="85" unit="line"/><space rend="indent1"/>To chace his adversaryes everychone;</l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Thei hem by land, thei hem by see asseyle.<note target="#6" type="footnotelink">6</note></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>The kyng his oratoure,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="81">G</note> <persName>God</persName> graunt his bone,<note type="gloss-indicator" n="82">G</note><space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="81">orator</gloss><gloss n="82"> prayer</gloss></l><l><space rend="indent1"/>Ay<note type="gloss-indicator" n="83">G</note> to prevaile in knyghthode and bataile. <space rend="indent1"/><gloss n="83">Always</gloss></l></lg>
 <lg><l><space rend="indent1"/>Amen.<note type="tnote-indicator" n="11">T</note> </l></lg>
 
